node.text:
An in-depth look at the vinyasa and alignment of Ashtanga’s #UtthitaParsvakonasana A&B, Extended Side Angle Pose, demonstrated by @vesic_jelena
-
🎥 @rubenlew 🙏
-
Check out our video on Ashtanga’s Fundamental Postures. The video explains:
•The traditional vinyasa counts and movements for each of the Fundamental Asanas
•The Tristhana (Three Places of Attention) for each count and posture
•Alignment cues and information to deepen your experience of the postures

Ultimately, the video is about much more than just the vinyasas and postures–  it’s about using precision and detail to help us tap into Ashtanga’s powerful technique of moving meditation.
⭐️https://www.davidrobsonyoga.com/product/perfecting-fundamentals-ashtanga-online-video/ ⭐️⭐️
-
I’m wearing @yogacrow and Jelena’s wearing @sulawear 🙏
-
#ashtanga #yogatutorial #yogawithdavid&jelena #vinyasa #alignment #yoga #sideanglepose #ashtangayoga

🚀 JUST LAUNCHED -- E-Sangha Fall Membership!
September, October, November 2021

Maintaining your home practice is much easier when you're guided by experienced teachers and surrounded by the support of others who share a passion for the practice, a sangha.

The aim of our E-Sangha is just that. To build an online community for Ashtanga students from all over the world to come together to learn and connect inside a supportive community.

The E-sangha Membership includes: 
• Virtual Mysore
• Led Primary
• Guided Meditation 
• Practice Clinic
• Conference
☆ Bonus: member exclusive offers and discounts!

One month and 3 month membership options available.

✨ Check out the full details and schedule by clicking the link in my bio.

---

FAQ's

What if I can't make the live class(es)?
• No worries. We record and upload each class for easy playback whenever works best for you. (Mysore excluded)

How long do I have access to the recordings?
• You will have access to the membership area for 2 weeks past the last live class date of your membership. 

Hope you will join us!

.
.

🎒Are you ready for Summer School?⁣
⁣⁣
For the second year in a row, we’re offering our most well-known course - 🌍 virtually!⁣⁣
⁣⁣
ASSISTING & ALIGNMENT SCHOOL⁣⁣
𝘑𝘶𝘭𝘺 𝟷𝟸 - 𝟹𝟷, 𝟸𝟶𝟸𝟷⁣⁣
⁣⁣

• Online Classes: Adjusting Techniques, Practice Teaching, Ashtanga Practice (Mysore + Led), Anatomy, and Listening Skills⁣⁣
• Assisting School Manual PDF⁣⁣
• Access to our Assisting & Alignment School discussion group⁣
• Certificate of Completion *new*⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣
𝐀𝐟𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐩𝐥𝐞𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐭𝐡𝐢𝐬 𝟑-𝐰𝐞𝐞𝐤 𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐬𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐲𝐨𝐮 𝐰𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐡𝐚𝐯𝐞:⁣⁣
✅ A deepened understanding of various adjustment techniques and modifications.⁣⁣
✅ The ability to detect alignment mistakes and know how to correct postures both verbally and physically with precise cueing taught by @vesic_jelena and I.⁣⁣
✅ An awareness of functional anatomy through training with expert Arielle Nash. @arielle_yoga_anatomy 
✅ The skills to actively listen to and help students from exploratory sessions with psychotherapist Sandra Pribanić. @ribapriba ⁣⁣
⁣⁣

-- Save $100 until June 30th!⁣⁣

⁣⁣

PASCIMATTANASANA (another one 🙃)

In our last #ashtangamondays post, @vesic_jelena and I said that if you’re pulling your bum out then you should put it back. 

We received some feedback that one part of the tutorial was a bit confusing, so we're offering another short tutorial to clear it up. 

⭐ First, (in Ashtanga) there is no vinyasa or specific cue to pull the bum out.  This would then be considered an extra movement, which is something we work to eliminate in the practice. 

⭐ Second, pulling the bum back is not always a healthy set up for forward bending. We want to keep the sit bones firmly grounded when we stretch the hamstrings, otherwise we risk over-stretching the tendons that attach the hamstrings to the sit bones. When the bum is pulled back there is a tendency to position the hips too far forward on the sit bones, and they can begin to lift away from the floor in the forward bend.

TIPS
When setting up for a forward bend: 
1: find a neutral position with your hips and spine (slight anterior tilt and lumbar extension)
2: activate your legs and press down through your your sit bones
3: pull in and down through your pubic bone
4: hinge at your hips as you fold, come forward, and not down, with your chest
